            <ul>
              <li><strong>Phenotype A (Full/Classic):</strong> All three features present; associated with the most pronounced metabolic dysfunction and highest insulin resistance.</li>
              <li><strong>Phenotype B:</strong> Ovulatory dysfunction plus hyperandrogenism (no polycystic morphology); metabolic profile similar to Phenotype A.</li>
              <li><strong>Phenotype C (Ovulatory):</strong> Hyperandrogenism plus polycystic morphology (regular ovulation preserved); milder metabolic impact.</li>
              <li><strong>Phenotype D (Non-hyperandrogenic):</strong> Ovulatory dysfunction plus polycystic morphology (no hyperandrogenism); the least metabolically severe phenotype.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Phenotyping informs RRM treatment intensity: Phenotypes A and B typically require insulin sensitization and more aggressive metabolic intervention; Phenotype C may respond to targeted hormonal support alone; Phenotype D often responds to ovulation induction without extensive metabolic workup.<sup><a href="#ref-39">39</a></sup></p>', NULL, NULL, 'published') ON CONFLICT(slug) DO UPDATE SET name=excluded.name, part=excluded.part, sort_order=excluded.sort_order, body_html=excluded.body_html, abbreviation=excluded.abbreviation, pillar_link=excluded.pillar_link, updated_at=datetime('now');

            <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS) and saline infusion sonohysterography (SIS) are the preferred diagnostic tools, both sensitive and cost-effective. SIS allows measurement of the defect dimensions and critically, the residual myometrial thickness (RMT). Treatment decisions depend on symptom profile, RMT, and future fertility desires.<sup><a href="#ref-43">43</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-16">16</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-15">15</a></sup></p>

            <p><strong>Treatment classification:</strong></p>
